\fs40 \cf2 I. Introduction: Optimizing Donkey Bridge's Didactic Core\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 Purpose: This report provides a comprehensive, research-informed analysis and a set of actionable recommendations designed to radically enhance the didactic effectiveness of the Donkey Bridge Thai language flashcard app. The primary focus is on maximizing the pedagogical value of personalized content generation, particularly through the refinement of the Set Wizard feature.\
Problem Statement: The current implementation of the Set Wizard, while conceptually sound in its aim for personalization, exhibits limitations in its pedagogical foundations. Specifically, its methods for assessing user proficiency and translating user-provided goals and preferences into genuinely personalized, level-appropriate, and goal-oriented learning content lack the necessary robustness and granularity [User Query]. This can result in generated flashcard sets that are not optimally aligned with the learner's actual needs, potentially hindering learning efficiency and engagement.\
Approach: To address these limitations, this report leverages established principles and contemporary findings from the fields of second language acquisition (SLA), educational technology, AI in education, and user interface/user experience (UI/UX) design. It proposes significant, evidence-based improvements to both the backend logic governing content generation and the frontend design facilitating user interaction. Existing assumptions within the current app design will be critically examined, and innovative solutions grounded in pedagogical research and best practices will be proposed.[1, 2, 3, 4]\
Report Structure Overview: The report begins by addressing foundational elements: enhancing proficiency assessment and goal definition. It then delves into the engineering of pedagogically sound content generation via advanced Large Language Model (LLM) prompting techniques. Subsequently, it examines UI/UX design principles for optimizing the learning environment, including the Set Wizard interface, user onboarding, and engagement strategies. A dedicated section explores the potential integration of a co-creative chatbot to further enhance personalization within the Set Wizard. The report concludes with a synthesis of recommendations and a strategic roadmap for implementation.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs40 \cf2 II. Foundational Enhancements: Assessing Proficiency and Defining Learning Goals\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0

\fs32 \cf2 A. Moving Beyond Static Levels: Implementing Dynamic Proficiency Assessment\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 Critique of Current Method: The app's current reliance on simple radio buttons ("Beginner," "Intermediate," "Advanced") for gauging user proficiency is a significant limitation [User Query]. These broad categories lack the necessary granularity and diagnostic capability to inform truly personalized content generation. They fail to capture the nuances of language ability, which rarely fits neatly into discrete boxes. Research and established practices in language assessment emphasize the need for more detailed frameworks.[5, 6, 7]\
Leveraging Standardized Frameworks (ACTFL/CEFR): To establish a more robust foundation, the integration of standardized proficiency frameworks is recommended. The American Council on the Teaching of Foreign Languages (ACTFL) Proficiency Guidelines and the Common European Framework of Reference for Languages (CEFR) are widely recognized as gold standards for describing language ability across various skills.[5, 7, 8] These frameworks have been empirically aligned [7, 9] and are used globally for assessment, curriculum development, and instruction. Efforts exist to map these frameworks to Thai language proficiency, such as the Chulalongkorn University Thai Proficiency Test (CU-TFL) [10, 11], demonstrating their applicability. Focusing on the Novice and Intermediate levels of the ACTFL scale (roughly corresponding to CEFR A1-B1/B2) is particularly relevant, as these encompass the proficiency ranges most commonly targeted by language learning applications.[7]\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Recommendation 1: Initial Self-Assessment via Can-Do Statements: Replace the current level selection with an interactive self-assessment module based on ACTFL/CEFR Can-Do Statements.[7] During onboarding or when creating a new profile, users would be presented with a series of "I can..." statements reflecting functional language abilities at different proficiency sublevels (e.g., Novice Low, Novice Mid, Novice High, Intermediate Low, etc.). Users select the statements that best describe their current abilities in Thai across relevant skills (listening, speaking, reading, potentially simplified for the app context). For example, a user might select "I can understand simple, everyday words and phrases related to familiar topics" (Novice Mid Interpretive) or "I can ask and answer simple questions on very familiar topics" (Intermediate Low Interpersonal).[7]\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Rationale: Can-Do Statements provide a learner-friendly [5, 7], concrete way for users to reflect on their functional language abilities, offering a more nuanced initial assessment than broad labels. They directly link assessment to real-world language use and align with internationally recognized benchmarks.[7, 12]\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Recommendation 2: Targeted Diagnostic Tasks: Following the initial self-assessment and the selection of learning goals (detailed in Section II.B), implement short, focused diagnostic tasks. These tasks should not aim for a comprehensive proficiency score but rather probe specific linguistic knowledge and skills relevant to the user's self-assessed level and chosen goals.[13, 14, 15]\
