\f0\b\fs32 \cf2 B. Structuring Goal Input: From Freeform to Focused Objectives\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf2 Critique of Current Method: The current approach of using freeform or multi-select inputs for learning goals, situations, and topics is inherently problematic for effective personalization [User Query]. Such inputs are often ambiguous, making it difficult for the backend system (and the LLM) to reliably interpret the user's intent. This frequently leads to the generation of generic or off-target flashcard content, even when the user attempts to be specific. Furthermore, this method fails to connect user-stated goals to concrete linguistic competencies or proficiency levels, hindering the creation of pedagogically sound learning pathways.[22, 23]\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Recommendation 5: Scenario-Based Goal Selection: Shift the primary goal input mechanism towards selecting from a curated list of relatable, real-world scenarios or communicative contexts.[24, 25] Examples could include: "Greeting People & Basic Introductions," "Ordering Food and Drinks," "Asking for and Understanding Directions," "Shopping for Souvenirs," "Making Small Talk about Hobbies," "Navigating Public Transport," "Discussing Daily Routines," or "Basic Business Etiquette."\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Rationale: Scenarios provide immediate, meaningful context for language use [25], making goal selection more intuitive for learners compared to abstract linguistic objectives. This approach aligns directly with communicative language teaching principles, focusing on language use in authentic situations.[11]\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Recommendation 6: Link Scenarios to Can-Do Statements: Internally, the app's backend logic should map each selectable scenario to relevant ACTFL/CEFR Can-Do statements.[7] Crucially, this mapping should be dynamic, considering the user's assessed proficiency range (from Section II.A). For instance:\
* A Novice High user selecting "Ordering Food and Drinks" might be mapped to Can-Do statements like: "I can ask for something I need in a simple way" [7]; "I can understand short, simple sentences... related to areas of most immediate need".[7]\
* An Intermediate Mid user selecting the same scenario might map to: "I can exchange information on familiar topics... using a series of connected sentences" [7]; "I can understand the main idea and some details of messages... on familiar topics".[7]\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Rationale: This crucial step connects the user-friendly scenario selection to concrete, measurable linguistic performance targets defined by established frameworks.[7] It provides clear, level-appropriate objectives to guide the LLM during content generation, ensuring pedagogical alignment.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Recommendation 7: Allow Topic Refinement (Optional): After a primary scenario is chosen, provide an optional step for the user to refine the focus with specific sub-topics or vocabulary themes. For example, under the "Ordering Food and Drinks" scenario, refinements could include "vegetarian food," "street food," "asking about ingredients," or "paying the bill."\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Rationale: This retains a degree of user control and allows for customization within the structured scenario framework, balancing pedagogical guidance with learner interest.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\cf2 Recommendation 8: Integrate Goals into User Profile: The selected scenario(s) and any topic refinements should be stored as part of the dynamic user profile, alongside their proficiency data.[22, 23]\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sa160\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0\cf2 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Rationale: This makes learning goals persistent, allowing the app not only to generate relevant initial sets but also to track the user's progress towards achieving specific communicative competencies over time. It supports a more holistic view of learning beyond simple vocabulary recall.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 A key advancement here is making goal selection adaptive based on the user's assessed proficiency. The app should intelligently present scenarios and associated Can-Do statements that are realistically achievable for the learner's current level.[7] A Novice learner selecting "Discussing Current Events," for example, might be gently guided towards more foundational scenarios first, or the app could map that goal to very basic Novice-level tasks within that complex topic (e.g., "I can recognize a few familiar names or words"). This prevents users from setting unrealistic goals and ensures the generated content remains within their zone of proximal development.\
Furthermore, by defining goals through the lens of framework-aligned Can-Do statements [7], the app establishes measurable 
\f2\i functional
\f1\i0  objectives. Progress tracking can then evolve beyond simply counting mastered flashcards to demonstrating the ability to perform specific communicative tasks associated with the chosen scenarios.[22, 26] This offers learners a much richer and more motivating understanding of their actual progress in using the Thai language, fulfilling the desire for enhanced didactic quality.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
