\f1\i0  The generated set should always be presented to the user for review and editing before saving [User Query]. This allows users to remove or modify cards they find unfunny, inappropriate, or simply ineffective. This is crucial for managing the unpredictability of humor generation.[56]\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0
\cf2 It's important to recognize that the "Seriousness" slider is not just controlling humor; it's implicitly managing linguistic register and formality. Serious communication typically employs more formal language, standard vocabulary, and adherence to politeness conventions.[34, 36] Comedic or highly informal communication often involves slang, colloquialisms, and deviations from standard politeness norms.[34, 48] Therefore, the prompt instructions derived from the slider must explicitly address these correlated linguistic features \'96 politeness markers (kr\'e1p/k\'e2), word choice, sentence structure \'96 not just the presence or absence of jokes or puns.\
Furthermore, ensuring reliable generation at both ends of the spectrum requires distinct strategies. Generating 
\f2\i useful
\f1\i0  serious content demands accuracy, adherence to standard usage, and practical relevance.[36] This might benefit from RAG grounded in standard dictionaries, phrasebooks, or corpora of formal Thai. Generating reliably 
\f2\i funny
\f1\i0  and culturally appropriate comedic content requires creativity, an understanding of Thai humor nuances [54, 55], and potentially access to different knowledge sources (e.g., examples of Thai wordplay, common jokes, appropriate slang via RAG, if feasible). The prompt structure itself might need slight variations depending on the slider's position to optimize for either dependable utility or effective humor.\
