\cf2 The true power of integrating a chatbot in this context lies in its ability to facilitate 
\f2\i iterative refinement
\f1\i0  and 
\f2\i co-creation
\f1\i0 .[2, 58] While the LLM can rapidly generate an initial set based on the structured prompt [1], user needs are often nuanced and evolve as they see the generated content [User Query]. The chatbot provides the conversational interface [62, 63] necessary for this back-and-forth refinement. Users can react to the LLM's output and request specific modifications ("make it funnier," "add a phrase about X," "simplify this example"), effectively using the chatbot to guide subsequent LLM prompts until the set meets their specific requirements. This transforms the user from a passive recipient of generated content into an active co-creator.\
However, designing the chatbot's personality requires a careful balancing act. While an engaging, perhaps humorous, personality aligned with the Donkey Bridge brand can enhance user motivation [81, 82, 91], the chatbot's fundamental purpose remains pedagogical.[38, 79] An overly playful or verbose chatbot could inadvertently increase the user's cognitive load [59] or distract from the primary task of creating an effective learning set. Therefore, the personality design must prioritize clarity, helpfulness, and support for the learning objectives. Humor and playfulness should be used strategically to enhance engagement and build rapport, but never at the expense of pedagogical effectiveness or clarity.[92]\
